A reducing scheme ℋ=(H,𝒜, ℒ) for a graph G
is a feasible reducing scheme (FRS) if there is a positive integer r such that


  * 	(H) ≤ r;

  * 	|I_ℋ| ≥ 2r, that is, G_ℋ has at most |V(G)|-2r vertices;  

  * 	𝒜 is a set of vertex-disjoint paths such that each P ∈𝒜 has an end vertex v 
				with odd degree in G_ℋ and V(P) ∖{v}⊆ I_ℋ;

  * 	for each path P∈ℒ with end vertices u and v,
				we have V(P)∖{u,v}⊆ I_ℋ. Moreover, for any pair of paths in 
				ℒ their parallel edges are distinct;


  * 	no vertex of I_ℋ is contained in more than one path of 𝒜∪ℒ.

In the case that ℋ=(H,𝒜, ℒ) is a feasible reducing scheme with
𝒜 = ℒ=∅, we say that H is a reducing subgraph (or an r-reducing subgraph ) of G.

