  ii) if 𝐯∈ℕ^d and 𝐯≠0, then 0≼𝐯.

Let S⊆ℕ^d be a generalized numerical semigroup. Given a relaxed monomial order ≼ in ℕ^d, we define:


 * 𝐅_≼(S) the greatest element in H(S) with respect to ≼, called Frobenius element of S with respect to ≼ (we write 𝐅_≼(ℕ^d)=(-1,…,-1) for convenience);

 * U_≼(S) the set of minimal generators greater than 𝐅_≼(S); 

 * 𝐦_≼(S) the smallest element of S∖{0} with respect to ≼, it is called multiplicity of S with respect to ≼.

A combinatorial substitution σ is connecting if, for each rule (P,Q,γ), the dual graph[The dual graph of a tiling is the graph whose vertices correspond to tiles of the tiling and whose edges connect vertices corresponding to adjacent tiles.] of Q has a subgraph N, called its network , such that


  * N is a star with one branch for each macro-facet, and the leaf of the k-th branch is a tile with a facet, called k-th port , in the k-th macro-facet of Q;

  * Each macro-facet has non-port facets, and removing the edges of N and its central vertex yields a connected graph which connects[One says that a subgraph connects a set of facets if these facets all belong to tiles which correspond to vertices of this subgraph.] all these facets;

  * the center of N corresponds to a tile in the interior of Q, called central tile ;

  * whenever two macro-tiles match along a port, they also match along the corresponding macro-facet.

