A ribbon graph G is a surface (possibly non-orientable) with boundary, represented as the union of two sets of closed topological disks called vertices V(G) and edges E(G), satisfying the following conditions:


 * edges and vertices intersect by disjoint line segments;


 * each such segment lies in the closure of precisely one edge and one vertex;


 * each edge contains two such segments.

Let I be a finite set. 
An I-labeled graph is a triple Γ = (V,ω,τ) where

  (i) V is a finite vertex set;

  (ii) ω : V× V → is a map;

  (iii) τ : V →(I) is a map assigning a subset of I to each vertex.

 An I-labeled graph Γ = (V,ω,τ) is quasi-admissible if 

  (a) it is reduced  in the sense that ω(x→ y) = 0 whenever τ(x)⊂τ(y).

  (b) its edge weights ω(x→ y) are all integers;

  (c) it is bipartite; 

  (d) the edge weights satisfy ω(x→ y) = ω(y→ x) whenever  τ(x)⊄τ(y) and τ(y)⊄τ(x).
The I-labeled graph Γ is admissible if  its integer edge weights are all nonnegative.
